{{manual|date=October 2013}}

{{C Standard Library}}
{{lowercase|title=stdarg.h}}

'''<code>stdarg.h</code>''' is a header in the [[C standard library]] of the [[C programming language]] that allows functions to accept an indefinite number of arguments.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.opengroup.org/onlinepubs/009695399/basedefs/stdarg.h.html | title=IEEE Std 1003.1 <code>stdarg.h</code> | accessdate=2009-07-04}}</ref> It provides facilities for stepping through a list of function arguments of unknown number and type.  [[C++]] provides this functionality in the header <code>cstdarg</code>.

The contents of <code>stdarg.h</code> are typically used in [[variadic function]]s, though they may be used in other functions (for example, <code>[[vprintf]]</code>) called by variadic functions.

==Declaring variadic functions==

[[Variadic functions]] are functions which may take a variable number of arguments and are declared with an [[ellipsis]] in place of the last parameter. An example of such a function is <code>[[printf]]</code>. A typical declaration is

<source lang="c">
int check(int a, double b, ...);
</source>

Variadic functions must have at least one named parameter, so, for instance,

<source lang="c">
char *wrong(...);
</source>

is not allowed in C. (In C++, such a declaration is permitted) In C, a comma must precede the ellipsis; in C++, it is optional.

==Defining variadic functions==
The same syntax is used in a definition:

<source lang=c>
long func(char, double, int, ...);

long func(char a, double b, int c, ...)
{
    /* ... */
}
</source>

An ellipsis may not appear in old-style function definitions.

